{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XrQMhWdzZ8rccCM2DM7DYX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of what's non-default:\n\n**Default RabbitMQ state:**\n- One vhost: `/`\n- One user: `guest` with administrator tag\n- No custom policies\n- No custom queues\n\n**Non-default configuration found:**\n1. **Extra vhosts:** `/app` and `/ops` (default is only `/`)\n2. **Extra users:** `app-user` (management tag) and `ops-user` (management tag) (default is `guest`)\n3. **Note:** `admin` with administrator tag is likely the cluster admin (replaces default `guest`) - but the default RabbitMQ setup has `guest` as the admin, not `admin`. \n\nI need to be cautious about removing the `admin` user since that would lock me out, even though the task is to revert non-default settings. Beyond the users and vhosts, there's a high-availability policy on `/app` that mirrors all queues automatically, plus custom permission grants for both the app and ops users across their respective vhosts.\n\nThe actual rollback plan is becoming clearer: I should delete the `ha-all` policy, remove the custom permissions for `app-user` and `ops-user`, delete those two users entirely, remove the queues they were using, and finally delete the `/app` and `/ops` vhosts. The `admin` user is tricky—it's likely a cluster admin created during installation rather than the default `guest` user, so I'll preserve it to avoid breaking the cluster.\n\nNow I'm writing the rollback script using rabbitmqctl commands to execute inside the rabbitmq-0 pod.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":655,"cache_read_input_tokens":33132,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":655},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"p